Question: 
Question 4 – Group Coding – Section: Generic Coding 2

A super virus is wreaking havoc across the world, and the race is on to find a cure. A novel approach to finding the cure relies on boosting the human body's immune system by destroying specific virus cells. To destroy a virus cell, one must first destroy other cells to which the virus cell is attached to (called prerequisites), some of which are virus cells and others are human cells. When a virus cell is destroyed, the immune system gets a positive boost, but when a human cell is destroyed, the immune system gets a negative boost. The goal is always to boost the immune system as much as possible. So, the only reason one would destroy a human cell with a negative boost is because it is a prerequisite to destroy a virus cell with higher positive boost.

There is no cyclicality in the prerequisites structure, e.g., it cannot happen that a cell a is to be destroyed for destroying cell b, b is to be destroyed for destroying cell c, and c is to be destroyed for destroying cell a.

Given a set of cells, your task is to find a subset of feasible target cells such that the boost to the immune system is the highest. A set of cells C is called feasible if for any cell i ∈ C, all the prerequisite cells of i are also included in C. The boost associated with C is the summation of the boosts for all cells in C.

Read the input from STDIN and print the output to STDOUT. Do not print arbitrary strings anywhere in the program, as these contribute to the output and test cases will fail.

Constraints
The number of cells X ≤ 10000
The total number of prerequisites of all cells is ≤ 5000
Input Format
The first line of input has X, the number of cells. The cells are labelled 1 to X.
The next X lines contain the information about the cells (in 1 to X sequence) in the following format:
the first number is the boost you gain by destroying that cell,
the second number is the number of prerequisites for that cell,
the remaining numbers are the prerequisites.
Output Format

A single line of output should print the maximum boost to the immune system that one can get by destroying a feasible set of cells.

Sample Input 1
3
2 1 2
3 1 3
-1 0
Sample Output 1
4
Explanation 1

The cells can be represented as follows, with the arrows representing the prerequisites. Before destroying C1, one must destroy C2, and before destroying C2 one must first destroy C3. C3 does not have any dependencies. The maximum boost possible is achieved by destroying all the three cells, and the boost is 2 + 3 - 1 = 4, which is printed as the output.

Sample Input 2
5
4 2 2 3
-3 0
2 1 5
-4 2 3 5
-5 1 2
Sample Output 2
0
Explanation 2

The cells can be represented as follows, with the arrows representing the prerequisites. Any feasible subset of cells here will produce only a negative boost; therefore, it is better not to destroy any cell, and keep the immunity boost as 0.

Sample Input 3
6
4 0
4 1 3
-5 2 4 5
-1 1 6
4 1 6
-2 1 1
Sample Output 3
4
Explanation 3

The maximum immunity boost is 4, achieved by destroying the subset of cells C5, C6, and C1.

Solution:
static class Edge {
    int to, rev;
    long cap;

    Edge(int to, int rev, long cap) {
        this.to = to;
        this.rev = rev;
        this.cap = cap;
    }
}

static class Dinic {
    ArrayList<Edge>[] g;
    int[] level, ptr;
    int n;

    Dinic(int n) {
        this.n = n;
        g = new ArrayList[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) g[i] = new ArrayList<>();
        level = new int[n];
        ptr = new int[n];
    }

    void addEdge(int u, int v, long cap) {
        g[u].add(new Edge(v, g[v].size(), cap));
        g[v].add(new Edge(u, g[u].size() - 1, 0));
    }

    boolean bfs(int s, int t) {
        Arrays.fill(level, -1);
        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        level[s] = 0;
        q.add(s);

        while (!q.isEmpty()) {
            int v = q.poll();
            for (Edge e : g[v]) {
                if (e.cap > 0 && level[e.to] == -1) {
                    level[e.to] = level[v] + 1;
                    q.add(e.to);
                }
            }
        }
        return level[t] != -1;
    }

    long dfs(int v, int t, long pushed) {
        if (pushed == 0) return 0;
        if (v == t) return pushed;

        while (ptr[v] < g[v].size()) {
            Edge e = g[v].get(ptr[v]);

            if (level[e.to] == level[v] + 1 && e.cap > 0) {
                long tr = dfs(e.to, t, Math.min(pushed, e.cap));
                if (tr > 0) {
                    e.cap -= tr;
                    g[e.to].get(e.rev).cap += tr;
                    return tr;
                }
            }
            ptr[v]++;
        }
        return 0;
    }

    long maxFlow(int s, int t) {
        long flow = 0;
        while (bfs(s, t)) {
            Arrays.fill(ptr, 0);
            while (true) {
                long pushed = dfs(s, t, Long.MAX_VALUE);
                if (pushed == 0) break;
                flow += pushed;
            }
        }
        return flow;
    }
}

public static int cureTheVirus(int n, int[] impact,
                               int[] numOfPre,
                               int[][] preCells) {

    int SRC = n;
    int SNK = n + 1;
    Dinic dinic = new Dinic(n + 2);

    long positiveSum = 0;
    long INF = 1000000000000L;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (impact[i] > 0) {
            dinic.addEdge(SRC, i, impact[i]);
            positiveSum += impact[i];
        } else if (impact[i] < 0) {
            dinic.addEdge(i, SNK, -impact[i]);
        }

        for (int j = 0; j < numOfPre[i]; j++) {
            int pre = preCells[i][j] - 1;   // input is 1-based
            dinic.addEdge(i, pre, INF);     // cell -> prerequisite
        }
    }

    long ans = positiveSum - dinic.maxFlow(SRC, SNK);
    return (int) ans;
}
